# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: binakol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:binakol/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:binakol/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:binakol/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:binakol/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:binakol/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:binakol/airline-chicken] The name of the cut is variously attributed to the shape resembling an airplane wing or that, because the exposed bone could be used as a handle to pick up the entire piece and eat it out of hand, it made it easier to eat in-flight.
[src:binakol/airline-chicken] The cut is also known as a *Frenched breast*, due to the end of the wing bone being trimmed or Frenched, or chicken supreme.
[src:binakol/airline-chicken] It is also known as Statler chicken, a name that originated from the Statler Hotel Boston, built in 1927 by E.M.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan is most well-known for Boracay, a resort island 0.8 kilometers north of the tip of Panay.
[src:binakol/aklan] It is known for its white sand beaches and is considered one of the more prominent destinations in the country.
[src:binakol/aklan] The Ati-Atihan Festival of Kalibo has also been known worldwide, hence declared "The Mother of all Philippine Festivals." It is an annual celebration held on the third Sunday of January to honor the Santo Niño (Infant Jesus).
[src:binakol/aklan] The festival showcases tribal dancing through the town's main streets to the tune of ethnic music, with participants in indigenous costumes and gear.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan is believed to have been settled in ancient times by settlers from Borneo, ruled by Datu Bangkaya, with his seat at Madyanos, near present-day Numancia.
[src:binakol/aklan] Several datus succeeded Datu Manduyog until the Spanish explorer Miguel López de Legazpi landed in Batan in 1565 and claimed the island for Spain, in early Spanish accounts it was called *El Río de Aclán*.
[src:binakol/aklan] According to an 1818 census, Aklan which was still in political union with the province of Capiz had municipalities with large amounts of Spanish-Filipino families, of which Batan had 56, Banga had 8, Malinao had 11, Kalibo had 167, and Ibajay 30.
[src:binakol/aklan] In 1942, the Japanese invaded Aklan during World War II.
[src:binakol/aklan] In 1945, combined Filipino and American army along with Aklanon guerrillas liberated Aklan during the war in the Pacific.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan (Akean) became an independent province through *Republic Act No.
[src:binakol/aklan] 1414* signed by Philippine President Ramon Magsaysay on April 25, 1956, separating Aklan from Capiz.
[src:binakol/aklan] The original towns were Altavas, Balete, Batan, Banga, Buruanga, Ibajay, Kalibo, Lezo, Libacao, Madalag, Malay, Makato, Malinao, Nabas, New Washington, Numancia, and Tangalan, then all part of the province of Capiz.
[src:binakol/aklan] The province was inaugurated on November 8, 1956.
[src:binakol/aklan] Jose Raz Menez was appointed the first governor of Aklan by President Magsaysay and he served until December 30, 1959.
[src:binakol/aklan] Ramos became the first elected governor but upon resigning to run for Congress he was succeeded by the vice governor, Virgilio S.
[src:binakol/aklan] Legaspi succeeded Patricio and he held office for two consecutive terms from 1964 to 1971.
[src:binakol/aklan] The beginning months of the 1970s had marked a period of turmoil and change in the Philippines, as well as in Aklan.
[src:binakol/aklan] During his bid to be the first Philippine president to be re-elected for a second term, Ferdinand Marcos launched an unprecedented number of foreign debt-funded public works projects.
[src:binakol/aklan] This caused the Philippine economy to take a sudden downwards turn known as the 1969 Philippine balance of payments crisis, which led to a period of economic difficulty and a significant rise of social unrest.
[src:binakol/aklan] With only a year left in his last constitutionally allowed term as president, Ferdinand Marcos placed the Philippines under Martial Law in September 1972 and thus retained the position for fourteen more years.
[src:binakol/aklan] This period in Philippine history is remembered for the Marcos administration's record of human rights abuses, particularly targeting political opponents, student activists, journalists, religious workers, farmers, and others who fought against the Marcos dictatorship.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklanons discovered that they could be arrested for even mundane things like being caught possessing a cassette tape of nationalistic songs.
[src:binakol/aklan] With no way to express their grievances about government abuses after the declaration of Martial law in 1972, many students felt they had no option but to join the underground resistance movement against the dicttorship.
[src:binakol/aklan] Some of these figures were later honored by having their names inscribed in the Philippines' Bantayog ng mga Bayani memorial which honors the martyrs and heroes who fought the authoritarian regime.
[src:binakol/aklan] 10, 1978, six years after the declaration of Martial Law under Ferdinand Marcos, 65 Philippine islands including Boracay was declared "tourist zones and marine reserves" without any mention of the status of the Ati who were the original residents of the island.
[src:binakol/aklan] This de facto dispossession of Ati lands on Boracay by Marcos placed the islands under the control of the Philippine Tourism Authority, and marked the beginning of rapid development on the island.
[src:binakol/aklan] In turn, this resulted in the further marginalization of the Boracay Ati for decades.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan was among the provinces affected by the COVID-19 pandemic in the Philippines, with an overseas Filipino worker who showed symptoms on March 12, 2020 becoming the first "person under investigation" (PUI) in the province.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan occupies the northern third of the island of Panay and is bordered by the provinces of Capiz from the southeast and Antique from the southwest.
[src:binakol/aklan] It also faces the Sibuyan Sea from the north.
[src:binakol/aklan] The province covers a total area of 1,821.42 square kilometres (703.25 sq mi), and includes the island of Boracay which is located at its northwestern tip.
[src:binakol/aklan] Located 6 km northwest of Mount Nausang and 4.8 km northeast of Mount Madja-as in Antique.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan River, is the longest river in the province with a total length of 91 km (57 mi) long.
[src:binakol/aklan] The province features high geographic diversity, ranging from white sandy beaches, mangroves and mountainous landscapes.
[src:binakol/aklan] Situated within the province is the river Akean, which appears unique due to its "boiling or frothing" appearance.
[src:binakol/aklan] The province is divided into two legislative districts for congressional representation.
[src:binakol/aklan] The population of Aklan in the 2024 census was 634,422 people, with a density of 350 inhabitants per square kilometre or 910 inhabitants per square mile.
[src:binakol/aklan] The main inhabitants of the province are the Aklanon, who are part of the Visayan ethnic group.
[src:binakol/aklan] Other inhabitants include the Negrito, locally known as the Ati and the Sulod, a lesser known tribal group living in the hinterlands of Panay.
[src:binakol/aklan] Other Visayans also present are the Hiligaynon, Karay-a, and Capiznon.
[src:binakol/aklan] Based on the 2000 census survey, Aklanon accounted for 96.56% (434,869) of the provincial population of 450,353.
[src:binakol/aklan] The most prominent languages in Aklan are Akeanon and its dialect Malaynon and the Buruanganon language.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklanon is spoken by a majority of the people, while Malaynon is spoken in Malay and Buruanganon is spoken in Buruanga.
[src:binakol/aklan] Hiligaynon is also widely spoken and understood in the province.
[src:binakol/aklan] Another language used is Ati, which is spoken by the tribe of the same name famous for the Ati-Atihan festival.
[src:binakol/aklan] Kinaray-a is spoken in the western part of the province bordering Antique.
[src:binakol/aklan] Capiznon is spoken in the eastern part of the province bordering Capiz.
[src:binakol/aklan] Filipino and English are used in administration and business as the national official languages.
[src:binakol/aklan] Roman Catholicism is the dominant religion of the people and Christian festivals such as Christmas and Lent are regarded with high importance.
[src:binakol/aklan] Meanwhile, Christian icons such as the *Santo Niño* are regarded as cultural symbols of the people.
[src:binakol/aklan] Animism, however, is still practised by the Ati.
[src:binakol/aklan] The Aglipayan Church or the Iglesia Filipina Independiente is the second most predominant religion in the province.
[src:binakol/aklan] Other religions in the province include Members Church of God International (MCGI), Iglesia ni Cristo, and Islam.
[src:binakol/aklan] The province of Aklan is designated as a first class province.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan depends on agriculture, with palay being the top produce in the province.
[src:binakol/aklan] Rice plantations had an area of 42,218 hectares (104,320 acres) (0.39 percent of the total provincial agricultural area).
[src:binakol/aklan] With the implementation of the Ginintuang Masaganang Ani (GMA) umaru rice production program using the Hybrid rice, production is expected to increase by 15 percent or an average of 10 metric tons per hectare in the succeeding years.
[src:binakol/aklan] However, the problem of low price support for rice still continues to affect the production sector.
[src:binakol/aklan] The decrease in production was attributed to the following factors: high cost of feeds, feed supplements and biologics, livestock and poultry diseases, increasing prices of chicks, and high cost of labor.
[src:binakol/aklan] Coconuts still occupy the largest area planted among major permanent agriculture crops.
[src:binakol/aklan] The total area planted with coconut is 32,276 hectares (79,760 acres).
[src:binakol/aklan] Ibajay ranks the largest with 4,317 hectares (10,670 acres); followed by Balete with 2,611 hectares (6,450 acres); Banga with umaru 2,314 hectares (5,720 acres); Makato with 2,089 hectares (5,160 acres); and, Altavas with 2,054 hectares (5,080 acres).
[src:binakol/aklan] All the rest of the municipalities have areas below 2,000 hectares (4,900 acres).
[src:binakol/aklan] However, in terms of copra production, Makato ranks number one with 2,770 metric tons per year; next is Balete with 2,669; and Libacao with 2,399.
[src:binakol/aklan] The rest produce less than 2000 metric tons.
[src:binakol/aklan] Total production is 25,375 metric tons annually.
[src:binakol/aklan] Other crops produced include bananas (*Lakatan*), mangoes, rambutan, and lanzones, as well as fiber crops such as piña fiber and abaca.
[src:binakol/aklan] Fishpond areas had a total area of 7,807.14 hectares (19,291.9 acres).
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan is a top producer of abaca, which are dyed and made into cloths or place mats, bags, wall decor and fans.
[src:binakol/aklan] The *piña* cloth, considered the "Queen of the Philippine Fabrics", is a prime produce of Kalibo, weaved from its unique crude wooden or bamboo handloom.
[src:binakol/aklan] Lezo is known for its red clay, used by the natives to make pots, vases and various novelty items.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan is accessible via highways and buses.
[src:binakol/aklan] Buses with routes from Iloilo, Capiz, and Antique connect Aklan with neighboring provinces.
[src:binakol/aklan] The Iloilo–Capiz–Aklan Expressway (ICAEx) is a proposed expressway on the island of Panay that will run from Iloilo City to Caticlan, Malay.
[src:binakol/aklan] A 1.2-kilometre (0.75 mi) limited-access bridge connecting Caticlan to Boracay is also being proposed by the Department of Public Works and Highways (DPWH) as part of its Public-Private Partnership (PPP) infrastructure projects.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan is famous for Boracay, a resort island 1 kilometre (0.62 mi) north of the tip of Panay.
[src:binakol/aklan] It is known for its white sandy beaches and is considered one of the most prominent destinations in the Philippines.
[src:binakol/aklan] Because of this, there is frequent air travel to the province's airports in Kalibo and Caticlan; Kalibo International Airport itself is about ten minutes from the main plaza.
[src:binakol/aklan] Kalibo Airport serves flights to and from Incheon in South Korea and Irkutsk and Khabarovsk in Russia through international flights served by T'way Air and IrAero.
[src:binakol/aklan] Despite the prevalence of Christianity, native beliefs about the *aswang* and the *babaylan* are still prevalent among the people.
[src:binakol/aklan] *Kulam* or witchcraft, locally known as *amulit* is still feared by many residents.
[src:binakol/aklan] Two main dishes associated with Aklan and Aklanons are inubaran and binakol.
[src:binakol/aklan] Inubaran, is a Filipino chicken stew or soup made with chicken cooked with diced banana pith, coconut milk (*gata*) or coconut cream (*kakang gata*), a souring agent, lemongrass, and various spices.
[src:binakol/aklan] The souring agent (called *aeabihig*) is traditionally either *batuan* fruits (*Garcinia morella*) or *libas* leaves (*Spondias pinnata*).
[src:binakol/aklan] The name means "[cooked] with *ubad* (banana pith)", not to be confused with *ubod* (palm heart); although *ubod* can sometimes be used as a substitute for *ubad* which can be difficult to acquire.
[src:binakol/aklan] Variants of the dish can also be made with other types of meat or seafood.
[src:binakol/aklan] Binakol, also spelled binakoe, is a Filipino chicken soup made from chicken cooked in coconut water with grated coconut, green papaya (or chayote), leafy vegetables, garlic, onion, ginger, lemongrass, and *patis* (fish sauce).
[src:binakol/aklan] *Binakol* can also be cooked with other kinds of meat or seafood.
[src:binakol/aklan] It was traditionally cooked inside bamboo tubes or directly on halved coconut shells.
[src:binakol/aklan] The province is known for its festivities which includes the Ati-Atihan festival in Kalibo.
[src:binakol/aklan] Originally, the festival was to celebrate the treaty between the Ati and the Malayan tribes who settled on the Island.
[src:binakol/aklan] The Ati live in the mountain regions and the Malay people in the flatlands or close to the water.
[src:binakol/aklan] The festivity begins in the dry season, at which time the Ati come down from the mountains to trade and celebrate with the Malayan tribes.
[src:binakol/aklan] When the Spaniards settled in the region and converted the Malays to their Christian religion, they asked the Malays to celebrate this festivity to coincide with the Feast of the Santo Niño (Holy Child) which is usually held during the third week of January.
[src:binakol/aklan] The Ati-Atihan Festival is a feast held annually in honor of the Santo Niño (Infant Jesus), held on the third Sunday of January in the town of Kalibo, Aklan, Philippines, on the island of Panay.
[src:binakol/aklan] It originally came from Batan, Aklan, then was adopted later by some neighboring towns.
[src:binakol/aklan] The name *Ati-Atihan* means "to be like Atis" or "to make believe Atis", the local name for the Aeta aborigines who first settled in Panay Island and other parts of the archipelago.
[src:binakol/aklan] The festival consists of tribal dance, music, accompanied by indigenous costumes and weapons, and a parade along the street.
[src:binakol/aklan] Christians and non-Christians observe this day with religious processions.
[src:binakol/aklan] The costumes worn at the festival are patterned after African tribal designs like those seen at the Rio Carnival in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.
[src:binakol/aklan] A 1200 A.D. event explains the origins of the festival.
[src:binakol/aklan] A group of 10 Malay chieftains called *Datus*, fleeing from the island of Borneo settled in the Philippines, and were granted settlement by the Ati people, the tribes of Panay Island.
[src:binakol/aklan] Datu Puti made a trade with the natives and bought the plains for a golden salakot, brass basins and bales of cloth.
[src:binakol/aklan] They gave a very long necklace to the wife of the Ati chieftain.
[src:binakol/aklan] Feasting and festivities followed soon after.
[src:binakol/aklan] Some time later, the Ati people were struggling with famine as the result of a bad harvest.
[src:binakol/aklan] They were forced to descend from their mountain village into the settlement below, to seek the generosity of the people who now lived there.
[src:binakol/aklan] In return, the Ati danced and sang for them, grateful for the gifts they had been given.
[src:binakol/aklan] The festivity was originally a pagan festival from this tribe practicing Animism, and their worshiping their anito god.
[src:binakol/aklan] Spanish missionaries gradually added a Christian meaning.
[src:binakol/aklan] Today, the Ati-Atihan is celebrated as a religious festival.
[src:binakol/aklan] In 2012, the National Commission for Culture and the Arts (NCCA) and the ICHCAP of UNESCO published *Pinagmulan: Enumeration from the Philippine Inventory of Intangible Cultural Heritage*.
[src:binakol/aklan] The first edition of the UNESCO-backed book included the *Ati-atihan Festival*, signifying its great importance to Philippine intangible cultural heritage.
[src:binakol/aklan] The local government of Aklan, in cooperation with the NCCA, was given the right to nominate the Ati-atihan Festival in the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists.
[src:binakol/aklan] The people attend masses for *Santo Niño*, and benefit dances sponsored by government organizations.
[src:binakol/aklan] The formal opening mass emphasizes the festival's religious event.
[src:binakol/aklan] The procession begins with a rhythmic drumbeats, and dances parading along the streets.
[src:binakol/aklan] The second day begins at dawn with a rosary procession, which ends with a community mass, and procession.
[src:binakol/aklan] Pwera Pasma!" is originally associated with the Sto.
[src:binakol/aklan] Nino Ati-Atihan Festival as the revelers and devotees keep on going with the festivities all over the town from morning to the wee hours of the next morning, rain or shine, for one week or even more.
[src:binakol/aklan] They believe that the miraculous Child Jesus will protect them from harm and illness.
[src:binakol/aklan] The highlight of the festival occurs on the third Saturday of January, when groups representing different tribes compete for tourists' attention and prizes.
[src:binakol/aklan] The festival ends with a procession of thousands of people carrying torches and different kinds of images of Santo Niño on the third Sunday.
[src:binakol/aklan] The contest winners are announced at a masquerade ball which officially ends the festival.
[src:binakol/aklan] Bariw Festival is a unique festival showcasing the skills of every Nabasnon in weaving bags, mats and hats made of *bariw* leaves – the prospering livelihood in the municipality.
[src:binakol/aklan] It is highlighted by the dance performances of local talent and ingenuity to the beat of the drums and indigenous rhythms celebrated every May 14 of the year.
[src:binakol/aklan] Bugna Festival is a festival showcasing the different locally produced products and eco-tourism destinations of Tangalan like the marine sanctuary and coral garden, Afga Point, Campo Verde, Jawili Falls, Bughawi beach and reforestation project every May 16 of the year.
[src:binakol/aklan] Kali-Ugyon Festival (*kali* stands for Kalipayan or happiness and *Ugyon* meaning "unity").
[src:binakol/aklan] This is the festival celebrated in Libacao every December 30 to January 1, costumed in modern and indigenous outfits bringing people together on the streets for merry-making and to drive away evil spirits in the coming New Year.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklanons are known for their literature, which includes the epic of Kalantiao.
[src:binakol/aklan] Cichon, Roman Aguirre, have produced several notable literary works in the province.
[src:binakol/aklan] Aklan is the home of the Regional Science High School for Region VI (RSHS-VI), one of the specialized system of public secondary schools in the Philippines.
[src:binakol/aklan] Several species endemic to the Philippines are found in the province.
[src:binakol/aklan] Examples include endangered animals such the Philippine spotted deer (*Cervus alfredi*), the Visayan warty pig (*Sus cebifrons*), and the Visayan hornbill (*Penelopides panini*).
[src:binakol/aklan] As of 2007, conservation efforts are being made by the Aklan State University and the DENR with varying success.
[src:binakol/aklan] Three mangrove species are in the World's Red List namely Avicennia rumphiana (Vulnerable), Ceriops decandra (Nearly Threatened) and Camptostemon philippinense (Endangered) are documented in the forest of Ibajay, Aklan.
[src:binakol/alaminos-longganisa] It is made with ground lean pork, ground pork fat, brown sugar, coarse salt, saltpeter, black pepper, bay leaf, vinegar, and garlic in hog casings.
[src:binakol/alaminos-longganisa] It is slightly sour, garlicky taste, typically bright yellow or orange due to the use of *achuete* seeds, made in bite-sized pieces.
[src:binakol/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is named after the Spanish “longaniza,” and is sometimes used interchangeably with the chorizo.
[src:binakol/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is a type of local sausage with two major types—the recado, with a more savory flavor, and the hamonado, with a sweet taste.
[src:binakol/alaminos-longganisa] Unlike other longganisa variants, the Alaminos longganisa's segments of the sausage are uniquely divided by small pieces of coconut leaf midribs (sometimes mistaken for toothpicks), making it easily identifiable.
[src:binakol/alaminos-longganisa] Each sausage string usually has six segments and is traditionally tied at the end with a length of buli palm fiber.
[src:binakol/alaminos-longganisa] The sausages are celebrated in an annual "Longganisa Festival" in Alaminos.
[src:binakol/alfajor] An ***alfajor*** or ***alajú*** (Spanish pronunciation: [alfaˈxoɾ], plural *alfajores*) is a traditional confection.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Originally from present-day Spain, it is found now in Argentina, Bolivia, Southern Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Ecuador, El Salvador, Southern France, Paraguay, Peru, the Philippines, Uruguay, and Venezuela.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The alfajor was born in Iberia during the rule of al-Andalus.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The Spanish alfajor is produced in the form of a small cylinder and is sold either individually or in boxes containing several pieces.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Traditional alfajores in Argentina, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn flour joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:binakol/alfajor] More modern "industrial" varieties in Uruguay and Argentina, are coated with dark or white chocolate (many *alfajores* are sold in "black" and "white" versions), or simply covered with powdered sugar.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The word had been introduced into Spanish dictionaries in the 14th century.
[src:binakol/alfajor] A similar sweet called *alaú* is found in the Arabic-Hispanic cookbook Kitab al-Tabikh, by an anonymous author.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The Spanish grammarian Nebrija noted the word for the first time in his Latin-Spanish Dictionary (1495) as: *alfaxor* or *alaxur*.
[src:binakol/alfajor] In the 12th century, Raimundo Martin describes in his book *Vocabulista* another possible etymology of the Hispano-Arabic *fasur*, meaning "nectar".
[src:binakol/alfajor] The publication of historical dictionaries of the Spanish language allows one to document both forms of the original *alajur*, written as *alajú* and *alfajor*.
[src:binakol/alfajor] *Alajur* and multiple geographic variations are sweets made of a paste of almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs and honey.
[src:binakol/alfajor] In the Americas, the word *alfajor* was not known until the 19th century.
[src:binakol/alfajor] In Spain, there are a variety of different recipes for preparing *alfajores*, but the most traditional contain flour, honey, almonds and several spices, such as cinnamon.
[src:binakol/alfajor] *Alfajores* are most commonly sold around Christmas.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The traditional Spanish *alfajor* has been produced in Medina-Sidonia (where it is called an *alajú*) since ancient times, and the recipe has been traditionally handed down from father to son.
[src:binakol/alfajor] In this town, there is an account of Mariano Pardo de Figueroa, writing under the pen name Dr.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Thebussem, wherein he wrote that on 2 July 1487, Enrique de Guzmán, second count of Medina Sidonia, ordered the council and majors of the region to send to Malaga 50 cows, 50 oxen, 200 calves and provision of *alajú* from his city.
[src:binakol/alfajor] On 15 September 2004, protected geographical indication was ratified by the *Consejo de agricultura y pesca de la junta de Andalucía* and published in the *Official Journal of the European Union* as *Alfajor de Medina Sidonia* on 6 March 2007.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The regulations of the Andalusian Ministry of Agriculture allow the use of only pure honey, almonds, nuts, breadcrumbs, sugar, flour and spices, such as aniseed, sesame, cilantro, cloves and cinnamon.
[src:binakol/alfajor] These *alfajores* are meant to be presented in a cylindrical shape, with a minimum weight of 30 grams (1.1 oz) each, and with a minimum size of about 7 centimetres (2.8 in) in length and a diameter of 1.5 centimetres (0.59 in).
[src:binakol/alfajor] Each of them will be protected with a wrapping paper, and the ends made an ornament in a spiral shape with a ribbon out of the same paper.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Once individually wrapped, they may be packaged in wood or cardboard boxes, but never in plastic.
[src:binakol/alfajor] In the province of Cuenca, Spain, where the *alfajor* is called *alajú,* it is made with almond, honey and figs, wrapped in a wafer.
[src:binakol/alfajor] In Puerto Rico, they underwent creolization, lost their almond and gained ground cassava.
[src:binakol/alfajor] They can take varying amounts of sugar and spices.
[src:binakol/alfajor] It is possible that Puerto Rico's most common version of this dessert (the South American version with dulce de leche) reached Puerto Rico from Venezuela, but the opposite is also possible.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Depending on region some add cornstarch, citrus zest, ginger and honey, filled with chocolate, vanilla cream, dulce de leche, fruit paste, or coconut.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The filling can be mixed with almonds, sesame seeds, coconut flakes, or sprinkles.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Traditional "alfajores" in Chile, Argentina,and Uruguay consist of two round, sweet biscuits made of wheat flour or corn starch joined with dulce de leche (known as "manjar blanco" in Peru and as "arequipe" in Venezuela), and optionally coated with powdered sugar.
[src:binakol/alfajor] These are also known as a *Chilean Oreo*.
[src:binakol/alfajor] One variation is called "*alfajor de nieve*" (snow alfajor) and has a white coating consisting of a mixture of egg whites and sugar.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Most *alfajores* come packaged in aluminium foil.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Alfajores are made in various diameters and are consumed as snacks.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The *alfajor* has been manufactured and consumed since colonial times in the territories that today belong to Argentina.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The filling is usually dulce de leche, although there are many variations.
[src:binakol/alfajor] They can be covered with powder sugar (the traditional ones), glazed sugar (Santafesinos or "de nieve"), grated coconut or chocolate.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Argentina is one of the world's largest consumers of alfajores, both in total numbers and in per capita calculations, consuming more than a billion alfajores a year.
[src:binakol/alfajor] One important Argentine alfajor is the alfajor de Santa Fe or the alfajor santafesino, which has three puff pastry layers adhered to one another with dulce de leche and glazed all over.
[src:binakol/alfajor] This alfajor is closely linked to the history of the city of Santa Fe.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Colonel Néstor Fernández from Santa Fe took it to the Battle of Caseros in 1851.
[src:binakol/alfajor] It became so popular with the army that General Justo José de Urquiza had a weekly shipment of these alfajores delivered to his estancia in San José de Entre Ríos.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The production of Santa Fe alfajores began in 1851 in a shop located on the southwest corner of San Jerónimo and 3 de Febrero streets, a few meters from the Cabildo (where the Santa Fe Government House currently stands).
[src:binakol/alfajor] These alfajores became known throughout the country after the 24 writers of the constitution, who, after living in Santa Fe for six months, took this dessert home as a souvenir.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Today, it is a heritage of the city of Santa Fe and is handcrafted in that city and its surrounding areas.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The nickname "Merengo" gave rise to a brand of alfajores.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The Cordobes alfajor is filled with fruit jellies (generally of quince).
[src:binakol/alfajor] In addition, there is the Rogel, similar to the Santa Fe but bigger (the size of a small cake) and a variety from Tucuman known as a clarita, with two crunchy cookies and filled with a jelly made up of sugar molasses.
[src:binakol/alfajor] In Argentina, alfajores made up of cornflour are very consumed as well (covers made up of maize starch, filled with dulce de leche and grated coconut around the filling).
[src:binakol/alfajor] Mass-production of alfajores traces back to the Atlantic coast of Argentina in the 1950s.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Brands such as Havanna and Balcarce, and as many as 30 others, have been introduced into shops and supermarkets.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Statistics of the year 2021 shows that inhabitants of Argentina consume 6 million alfajores per day.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Two types of alfajores are found in Chile.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The first type of alfajor, similar to the one of corn flour prepared in other countries of Latin America, is prepared over all the territory of Chile, but mainly in the central area of Chile.
[src:binakol/alfajor] It is known as "candy of corn flour" or, more typically, "chilenitos".
[src:binakol/alfajor] The chilenitos are manufactured with corn flour or other types of flour and tend to be simpler and smaller than the other alfajores.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The second type of alfajor, considered the true traditional alfajor of the country and known as "chilean alfajor", is mainly prepared in the southern areas of Chile, generally for the patriotic festivities of September.
[src:binakol/alfajor] It is prepared with two hojarascas (a thin and firm cookie) that, since they are previously baked, acquire a curved form.
[src:binakol/alfajor] They are adhered to each other with dark brown sugar, panela, manjar or with confectioners cream.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Optionally, they can be garnished in the end of the filling with grated coconut as it is the case of the alfajores filled with manjar or with ground nuts.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Alfajores made their arrival to the Viceroyalty of Peru, the largest administrative district of the Spanish Empire in South America in the 16th century, and have been popular since, especially the artisanal types.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Alfajor de Trujillo is a type of alfajor from Trujillo.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The *alfajor de Trujillo* has several layers and it can be of different sizes and shapes as round or square.
[src:binakol/alfajor] It is made mainly with products as flour, butter, eggs and milk, filled with milk candy, some pineapple sweet and in some cases peanuts, with cookies within its layers.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The most famous company manufacturing this products in Trujillo is Dulcería Castañeda, which has locations in Trujillo and Lima and has been making them since 1925.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The mass of the alfajor is made of flour, eggs, margarine, salt, and water.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The filling is made with figs, quince, walnuts, blancmange.
[src:binakol/alfajor] It is one of the products presented in the Gastronomic Fair in Trujillo.
[src:binakol/alfajor] Another variant of the alfajor de trujillo is King Kong milk candy, which is made in both Trujillo and Lambayeque.
[src:binakol/alfajor] According to Guinness World Records, the biggest *alfajor* in the world, measuring almost 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) in diameter and 80 centimetres (31 in) in height and weighing 464 kilograms (1,023 lb), was made on 11 December 2010 in Minas, Lavalleja Department, Uruguay.
[src:binakol/alfajor] The giant *alfajor* was made to mark the celebration of Uruguay's first National Alfajor Festival.
[src:binakol/alfajor] More than 30 people participated in the preparation of the record-breaking *alfajor*.
[src:binakol/binakol] The dish is similar to *tinola* and *ginataang manok*, except that the latter two use water and coconut milk, respectively, instead of coconut water.
